                  <Text layoutX="45.0" layoutY="1369.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="1. Primary Memory" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="927.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Memory is the backbone of your computer’s performance. Here’s why it matters:" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="1143.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="When you open a program, it is loaded from secondary memory into primary memory. Because there are various types of memory and storage, an example would be moving a program from a solid-state drive (SSD) to RAM. Because primary storage is accessed more quickly, the opened software can connect with the computer's processor more quickly. The primary memory is readily accessible from temporary memory slots or other storage sites." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="1402.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="It is also known as the main memory of the computer system. It is used to store data and programs, or instructions during computer operations. It uses semiconductor technology and hence is commonly called semiconductor memory. Primary memory is of two types:" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="1893.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="It is also known as auxiliary memory and backup memory. It is a non-volatile memory and used to store a large amount of data or information. The data or information stored in secondary memory is permanent, and it is slower than primary memory. A CPU cannot access secondary memory directly. The data/information from the auxiliary memory is first transferred to the main memory, and then the CPU can access it." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="2017.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Types of Secondary Memory" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="2051.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="1. Magnetic Tapes: Magnetic tape is a long, narrow strip of plastic film with a thin, magnetic coating on it that is used for magnetic recording. Bits are recorded on tape as magnetic patches called RECORDS that run along many tracks. Typically, 7 or 9 bits are recorded concurrently. Each track has one read/write head, which allows data to be recorded and read as a sequence of characters. It can be stopped, started moving forward or backwards or rewound." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="30.0" layoutY="350.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="3.2 Common Input and Output Devices" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="383.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Input devices are the devices that are used to send signals to the computer for performing tasks. The receiver at the end is the CPU (Central Processing Unit), which works to send signals to the output devices." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="447.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Some of the classifications of Input devices are:" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="468.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Keyboard Devices" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="489.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Pointing Devices" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="510.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Webam" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="554.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Output Devices are the devices that show us the result after giving the input to a computer system. Output can be of many different forms like image, graphic audio, video, etc. Some of the output devices are described below." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="629.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Monitor" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="659.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Monitors, also known as Visual Display Units (VDUs), are a computer's primary output device. It creates images by arranging small dots, known as pixels, in a rectangular pattern." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="716.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Printer" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="747.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Printers are output devices that allow you to print information on paper. There are certain types of printers which are described below." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="52.0" layoutY="800.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Speakers" textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
